 at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC using a premium index methodology. The exchange applies zero maker fees, allowing arbitrageurs to enter positions cost-effectively when exploiting rate differentials. Funding payments are settled automatically between long and short position holders based on the 8-hour average rate. MEXC's funding rate caps typically range from -2% to +2% per funding period to prevent extreme rate scenarios."}]]}],"$L3",["$L4","$L5","$L6"],"$L7"]}],"$L8"]}]]}],["$L9","$La"],"$Lb"]}],"loading":null,"isPartial":false}
3:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","IMX","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"IMX represents exposure to the Immutable X gaming ecosystem, creating distinct funding patterns compared to DeFi or infrastructure tokens. Gaming tokens often experience episodic volatility around game launches or partnership announcements, leading to temporary funding rate spikes. MEXC's early listing advantage for gaming tokens means IMX/USDT often shows higher volatility and funding rate opportunities compared to more established exchanges."}]]}]
4:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"IMX/USDT funding rates on MEXC have shown significant volatility, particularly during gaming sector rallies and major Immutable X ecosystem updates. Rates typically range from -0.5% to +1.2% per 8-hour period, with extreme spikes reaching +2% during high speculation periods. Gaming token funding rates generally exhibit higher variance than infrastructure tokens due to retail-driven sentiment cycles. Weekend funding rates tend to normalize as institutional activity decreases, creating predictable arbitrage windows for patient traders."}]]}]
5:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's zero maker fees create compelling arbitrage setups when IMX funding rates diverge significantly from other exchanges like Binance or OKX. The most profitable opportunities typically occur during gaming sector news events when MEXC's retail-heavy user base drives sentiment-based position imbalances. Cross-exchange funding rate spreads of 0.3%+ per 8-hour period can generate meaningful returns when combined with MEXC's fee structure. Traders should monitor IMX's correlation with broader gaming tokens like AXS and SAND to identify sector-wide funding rate anomalies."}]]}]
6:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's thinner order books for IMX/USDT create heightened slippage risks during large arbitrage position entries and exits. The exchange's volume reporting practices raise questions about true liquidity depth, potentially leading to execution difficulties during volatile periods. Gaming tokens like IMX face regulatory uncertainty as Web3 gaming business models evolve, creating additional fundamental risks beyond typical funding rate arbitrage. Traders should implement strict position sizing and monitor MEXC's operational stability, particularly during high-volume gaming sector events."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lc",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often does MEXC update IMX/USDT funding rates?","answer":"MEXC updates IMX/USDT funding rates every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC. The rates are calculated using an 8-hour time-weighted average premium and applied automatically to all open perpetual positions."},{"question":"What makes IMX funding rates different from other gaming tokens on MEXC?","answer":"IMX funding rates reflect the token's role in Ethereum L2 gaming infrastructure rather than individual game performance. This creates more stable funding patterns compared to game-specific tokens, though still higher volatility than general infrastructure tokens during gaming sector movements."},{"question":"How do MEXC's zero maker fees impact IMX funding rate arbitrage?","answer":"Zero maker fees allow arbitrageurs to enter and exit IMX positions without trading costs, making smaller funding rate differentials profitable. This fee structure is particularly beneficial for high-frequency funding rate strategies that require frequent position adjustments."},{"question":"What IMX/USDT position sizes can MEXC handle for funding rate strategies?","answer":"MEXC's IMX/USDT order book typically supports positions up to $50,000 USD equivalent without significant slippage during normal conditions. Larger positions should be executed gradually or during high-volume periods to minimize market impact costs that could erode funding rate arbitrage profits."}]}]
